<center>Druid of the 60th Ring <br>
<center> Resident of The Tribunal <br></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=radgen>Radgen</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/misc_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I read boards more<br>than I play EQ....</span><br>  Posts: 570<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/18/03 3:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=427.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://radgen.homestead.com/files/Radgen5.jpg height=150 width=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: North Korea plans to build four more nuclear reactors</span><hr size=1> One other thing about A-bombs.  Is where the real complexity and difficulty crops up.  This depends heavily on what kind of bomb you are making.  Implosion or &quot;gun&quot;.<br>
<br>
u-235 is use in &quot;gun&quot; type bombs.  The advantage here is the construction of such bombs is simple and very reliable.  To the point that a &quot;tet&quot; may not be needed to determine if your design will work.  The downside is U-235 enrichment is difficult, complex and has low yields.<br>
<br>
Plutonium is used in implosion type bombs.   There advantage is it is reletively easy to produce Plutonium (all you need is a reactor) and you can produce a large amount in a very short period of time.  The drawback is that implosion type bombs are complex pieces of engineering and without testing, there is no reliable way to know if your design will actually fire.<br>
<br>
The decision on which one to make is complex.  Plutonium is prefered because the yields and ease of production.  Especially if you already have a civilian nuke program to act as &quot;cover&quot;.  But the need to test means that there is little chance of keeping an aresenal secret unless you want to risk haveing a bunch of duds.<br>
<br>
u-235 has the distince advantage of NOT needing the give away presense of a Nuclear reactor, allowing bomb development to be hidden easier.   Also the simplicity of the &quot;gun&quot; type bomb means that testing a completed bomb is not strictly needed.  The only problem with this scenerio is that the yields on U-235 production is so low that it can take years just to get enough for one bomb.  Bigger facilities can increase the yield, but get to big and no reactor or not, everyone is going to figure out what you are doing.<br>
<br>
As far as the fuel NK is suspected of haveing from before the agreements were put into place.  There is one minor bright side to it.  It is plutonium, used in implosion type bombs.  While they may have used this to make bombs, without an actual test, it is real iffy on how well they will work.  they could both be duds, or they could both work.  Niether us OR the NK's are going to know till they try to set one off. <p><center><font face="lucida handwriting, arial" color="006800" size=+2><b>Radgen Waldjaeger</font></b><br><font face="tempus sans ITC, arial" color="675f00" size=+1><b>Semi-retired Pathfinder of Karana</font><br><font face="tempus sans ITC, arial" color="blue" size=+1>Shining Path</font></b><br><img src=http://radgen.homestead.com/files/tiger_run_md_clr.gif></center>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=radgen>Radgen</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/misc_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I read boards more<br>than I play EQ....</span><br>  Posts: 571<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/18/03 4:03 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=427.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://radgen.homestead.com/files/Radgen5.jpg height=150 width=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: North Korea plans to build four more nuclear reactors</span><hr size=1> More not so good news on the NK front<br>
