</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=maxamaji>MaxaMaji</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalWhite.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>For the record,<BR>
I disagree with<BR>
everything you <BR>
just said</span><br>  Posts: 779<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/18/03 9:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=427.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: North Korea plans to build four more nuclear reactors</span><hr size=1> Radgen, most of that is actually completely backwards. <br>
<br>
-It does not take years to enrich U, however Pu takes years to make especially in a low MW commercial reactor. There is one type that will make it fairly quickly, which is a fast breeder, and operation of fast breeders is very constrained by international agreements. NK does not have a fast breeder. U enrichment is not rocket science like the news would lead you to believe. What's rocket science about it is doing it without killing everyone working in the enrichment lab in a matter of months or years. If you don't have a problem with that you can do it fairly quickly. The bottom line is you have to already have U to make Pu in any worthwhile amount.<br>
<br>
-Either U or Pu can be used in either a gun or implosion weapon, it is not one or the other. Get either above it's critical nuclear density by any means and it will go prompt critical and increase from its quiescent thermal power output at about 7000 decades (powers of ten) per minute. The US has trigger pits in weapons as we speak that are U implosion devices.<br>
<br>
-Equivalent weapon yield for U is lower than Pu, but it's fairly insignificant with the differences in difficulty of obtaining U vs Pu, and the change in weapon dimensions is small. i.e. if you can deliver a Pu bomb you can deliver a U bomb.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
I'm going to say this really loud for Loegan, so please excuse me. Actually never mind, defending Clinton is more important than actually knowing anything here so I'll just say it. I don't feel like looking at a lot of caps.<br>
<br>
1) Uranium is *already* a fissile material, and if you have a reactor, 99% chance you already have uranium. Enriching it is not hard, we do it by the tens of tons every year and could by the hundreds if we needed, but we don't need to. We bred lots of Pu in the US because we had the capability to do it easily (lots of reactors that can do it relatively efficiently) and we had all the time and resources in the world.<br>
<br>
2) The only use for a reactor at all in weapon production is for neutron bombardment of U238 to create Pu239, however you *do not need* a reactor to do it. Nowhere in a weapons program do you actually have to have a reactor. There is an equation for how fast you can make Pu, it's (very ballparkishly) low thermal neutron flux density (how many neutrons are in a given volume at any given time) times how much U238 there is in that given volume. In a nutshell, how many neutrons of the right energy to undergo capture (vice cause fission, elastic collision, etc.) by a U238 nucleus there are, times how many U238 nuclei there are to capture them. It's a giant equation but thats the gist of it<br>
<br>
3) See the first sentence of #1.<br>
<br>
Another thing of note left out is that the biggest danger of working with plutonium, even more than the emissions, is that it is a deadly poison.<br>
<br>
It's nice that you cut and pasted all that for us. The enrichment processes were pretty much right although some are much better than others, the critical masses were ballpark but not very representative because the mass needed to achieve supercriticality is dependent on a whole truckload of things, and the production amounts were straight out of someones ass. That is super-controlled information in any country and any numbers on Pu production capability you find on the internet are guaranteed to be wild speculation.<br>
<br>
If NK has a plutonium fission device of any type, the only thing that means is that their programs started *even farther* back into Clinton's administration than it had to have if they have a uranium fission device. My own speculation says they most likely have sub-40kt U-implosion fission weapons because implosion triggered weapons are just not that hard for a reasonably technological country to make once they have the fissile material, and &quot;gun triggers&quot; are inefficient. But like I said that's only speculation. It's doubtful they have anything thermonuclear, but anything's possible I guess.<br>
<br>
I've worked in this field for almost 15 years now and have no problem talking about it as long as it's not something that could get me in trouble. You would be surprised now much info on it is not classified, just not well known. And you're not going to find it on the internet lol. I'm tired of people getting &quot;facts&quot; off the internet and posting them as such, telling me I'm wrong and I feel pretty much stupid trying to explain it anymore because it's a waste of my time to type a response to it and a waste of anyone's time that reads it because the misinformation is misleading. If anyone wants to know something about it I'll do my best as long as it's a part of the process I'm familiar with and it's not something I shouldn't be saying, otherwise I'll just chuckle and make a wisecrack. That's much more easy and fun anyway. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=loeganwolfheart>Loegan Wolfheart</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Please do things my way, thx.</span><br>  Posts: 2379<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/18/03 11:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=427.topic&index=30>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://loegan.homestead.com/files/rn.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: North Korea plans to build four more nuclear reactors</span><hr size=1> You missed the whole point Max. That's ok, let me walk you through it:<br>
