<br>
NK was presuing their nuclear program for several years.  NK acted accordingly (IE signing this agreement, signing that agreement) appeasing everyone's suspicions.  An agreement was being designed to grant inspection rights to the IAEA in 1992.  Things came to a halt in Jan 1993, when NK refused to allow inspections of two undeclared faclities, that were said to contain nuclear waste.  It doesn't say in the article what these facilities may have been, but it seems these two facilities were part of a nuclear weapons program.<br>
<br>
A lot of saber rattling from NK for a couple of years, their &quot;President&quot; dies as well, which leads to further complications.<br>
<br>
On April 22 1994 NK and US sign an agreement.  At this point it was already determined by US intelligence that NK had already produced enough plutonium for at least one nuclear weapon.  But there is talk in the article that states figures that leads to the possibility of NK having produced enough for at least 3 weapons.  This agreement lead NK to announce that they froze their nuclear weapons program in 1995.<br>
<br>
Fast forward to Oct 2002 (long before the &quot;Axis of Evil&quot; speech), NK announces that they had a secret nuclear weapons program running.  Again, it doesn't state exactly when NK had this program running, mainly because NK didn't say, but I'd make a bet that it was running shortly after the 1994 agreement.<br>
<br>
So essentially, the efforts that Bush Sr administered lead to talks that Clinton administered, which created an agreement where South Korea pays the lion's share of cost to construct two nearly free reactors in NK.  NK responds with so much gratitude that they create a secret nuclear weapons program, which they then announce it's existance in Oct 2002.<br>
<br>
They are pieces of shit, pure and simple.  Clinton did his best diplomacy work, but you can't make solid deals with pieces of shit.  Now they have possible nukes, and Bush Jr must deal with them somehow.  It's obvious that you can't make agreements with them, but it's also pretty clear that you can't straight up strong arm them.  Seems like a pretty shitty situation, be glad you aren't in charge.<br>
<br>
BTW, have you seen how aged Bush looks these days?<br>
